SUSTAINABILITY AND MINDFULNESS PERTAINS TO CLOTHES, TOO
//
If I ever post about clothing, it will be on the topic of minimalism and sustainability. In the last few years, I’ve learned the immense pollution and human abuse behind the fashion industry. I recommend everyone watch The True Cost for an eye-opening overview.
//
I’ve also chosen not to support many mainstream clothing brands or wear clothes with visible logos, because the brands employ and advertise models with eating disorders. I don’t stand for that, what I purchase speaks to my values.
//
I own about 25 pieces of clothing, all high-quality pieces made with primary natural fibers (instead of polluting synthetic fibers). I’m inspired by the European fashion ethos, which encourages fewer and higher quality pieces.
//
I feel the same about my accessories: I have my rings I wear 24/7, two necklaces, 2 pairs of earrings.
//
“Fast fashion” (google it) encourages us to consume clothing mindlessly. When we do that, we mindlessly consume earth’s resources, participate in inhuman employment practices, and turn a blind eye to marketing which promotes disordered eating.
//
And now, if someone will get me a ladder, I’ll climb down from this soapbox.
